\
**How to assign colors**: Color should encode meaning\cf2 \strokec2 ,\cf4 \strokec4  not sequence. Don't cycle through colors like a rainbow (step \cf7 \strokec7 1\cf4 \strokec4  = blue\cf2 \strokec2 ,\cf4 \strokec4  step \cf7 \strokec7 2\cf4 \strokec4  = amber\cf2 \strokec2 ,\cf4 \strokec4  step \cf7 \strokec7 3\cf4 \strokec4  = red...). Instead:\
- Group nodes by **category** \'97 all nodes of the same type share one color. E.g. in a vaccine diagram: all immune cells = purple\cf2 \strokec2 ,\cf4 \strokec4  all pathogens = coral\cf2 \strokec2 ,\cf4 \strokec4  all outcomes = teal.\
- For illustrative diagrams\cf2 \strokec2 ,\cf4 \strokec4  map colors to **physical properties** \'97 warm ramps for heat/energy\cf2 \strokec2 ,\cf4 \strokec4  cool for cold/calm\cf2 \strokec2 ,\cf4 \strokec4  green for organic\cf2 \strokec2 ,\cf4 \strokec4  gray for structural/inert.\
- Use **gray for neutral/structural** nodes (start\cf2 \strokec2 ,\cf4 \strokec4  end\cf2 \strokec2 ,\cf4 \strokec4  generic steps).\
- Use **\cf7 \strokec7 2-3\cf4 \strokec4  colors per diagram**\cf2 \strokec2 ,\cf4 \strokec4  not \cf7 \strokec7 6\cf4 \strokec4 +. More colors = more visual noise. A diagram with gray + purple + teal is cleaner than one using every ramp.\
- **Prefer purple\cf2 \strokec2 ,\cf4 \strokec4  teal\cf2 \strokec2 ,\cf4 \strokec4  coral\cf2 \strokec2 ,\cf4 \strokec4  pink** for general diagram categories. Reserve blue\cf2 \strokec2 ,\cf4 \strokec4  green\cf2 \strokec2 ,\cf4 \strokec4  amber\cf2 \strokec2 ,\cf4 \strokec4  and red for cases where the node genuinely represents an informational\cf2 \strokec2 ,\cf4 \strokec4  success\cf2 \strokec2 ,\cf4 \strokec4  warning\cf2 \strokec2 ,\cf4 \strokec4  or error concept \'97 those colors carry strong semantic connotations from UI conventions. (Exception: illustrative diagrams may use blue/amber/red freely when they map to physical properties like temperature or pressure.)\
\
**Text on colored backgrounds:** Always use the \cf7 \strokec7 800\cf4 \strokec4  or \cf7 \strokec7 900\cf4 \strokec4  stop from the same ramp as the fill. Never use black\cf2 \strokec2 ,\cf4 \strokec4  gray\cf2 \strokec2 ,\cf4 \strokec4  or --color-text-primary on colored fills. **When a box has both a title and a subtitle\cf2 \strokec2 ,\cf4 \strokec4  they must be two different stops** \'97 title darker (\cf7 \strokec7 800\cf4 \strokec4  in light mode\cf2 \strokec2 ,\cf4 \strokec4  \cf7 \strokec7 100\cf4 \strokec4  in dark)\cf2 \strokec2 ,\cf4 \strokec4  subtitle lighter (\cf7 \strokec7 600\cf4 \strokec4  in light\cf2 \strokec2 ,\cf4 \strokec4  \cf7 \strokec7 200\cf4 \strokec4  in dark). Same stop for both reads flat; the weight difference alone isn't enough. For example\cf2 \strokec2 ,\cf4 \strokec4  text on Blue \cf7 \strokec7 50\cf4 \strokec4  (#E6F1FB) must use Blue \cf7 \strokec7 800\cf4 \strokec4  (#0C447C) or \cf7 \strokec7 900\cf4 \strokec4  (#042C53)\cf2 \strokec2 ,\cf4 \strokec4  not black. This applies to SVG text elements inside colored rects\cf2 \strokec2 ,\cf4 \strokec4  and to HTML badges\cf2 \strokec2 ,\cf4 \strokec4  pills\cf2 \strokec2 ,\cf4 \strokec4  and labels with colored backgrounds.\
\
**Light/dark mode quick pick** \'97 use only stops from the table\cf2 \strokec2 ,\cf4 \strokec4  never off-table hex values:\
- **Light mode**: \cf7 \strokec7 50\cf4 \strokec4  fill + \cf7 \strokec7 600\cf4 \strokec4  stroke + **\cf7 \strokec7 800\cf4 \strokec4  title / \cf7 \strokec7 600\cf4 \strokec4  subtitle**\
- **Dark mode**: \cf7 \strokec7 800\cf4 \strokec4  fill + \cf7 \strokec7 200\cf4 \strokec4  stroke + **\cf7 \strokec7 100\cf4 \strokec4  title / \cf7 \strokec7 200\cf4 \strokec4  subtitle**\
- Apply `c-\cf2 \strokec2 \{\cf4 \strokec4 ramp\cf2 \strokec2 \}\cf4 \strokec4 ` to a `<g>` wrapping shape+text\cf2 \strokec2 ,\cf4 \strokec4  or directly to a `<rect>`/`<circle>`/`<ellipse>`. Never to `<path>` \'97 paths don't get ramp fill. For colored connector strokes use inline `stroke=\cf5 \strokec5 "#..."\cf4 \strokec4 ` (any mid-ramp hex works in both modes). Dark mode is automatic for ramp classes. Available: c-gray\cf2 \strokec2 ,\cf4 \strokec4  c-blue\cf2 \strokec2 ,\cf4 \strokec4  c-red\cf2 \strokec2 ,\cf4 \strokec4  c-amber\cf2 \strokec2 ,\cf4 \strokec4  c-green\cf2 \strokec2 ,\cf4 \strokec4  c-teal\cf2 \strokec2 ,\cf4 \strokec4  c-purple\cf2 \strokec2 ,\cf4 \strokec4  c-coral\cf2 \strokec2 ,\cf4 \strokec4  c-pink.\
